'''Philipp Lienhart''' (born 11 July 1996) is an Austrian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre back|centre-back]] for {{German football updater|SCFreibu}} club [[SC Freiburg]]  and the [[Austria national football team|Austria national team]].

==Club career==

===Rapid Wien===
Born in [[Lilienfeld]], [[Lower Austria]], Lienhart joined [[SK Rapid Wien]]'s youth setup in 2008, aged 12. He made his senior debut for their [[reserve team]] on 16 April 2013, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 3–3 away draw against [[FC Admira Wacker Mödling Amateure]] for the [[Regionalliga (Austria)|Regionalliga]] championship.

===Real Madrid===
In August 2014, after being regularly used, Lienhart was loaned to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defensacentral.com/la_fabrica/110651-castilla-refuerza-cesion-philip-lienhart/|title=El Castilla se refuerza con la cesión de Lienhart|trans-title=Castilla bolsters with the loan of Lienhart|publisher=Defensa Central|language=es|date=31 August 2014|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> He competed with [[Real Madrid Juvenil|their youth team]] in [[2014–15 UEFA Youth League|the season]]'s [[UEFA Youth League]], playing seven matches and scoring in a 3–2 loss away to Liverpool in the group stage on 22 October, and also appeared with [[Real Madrid C|the C-side]] in [[Tercera División]].

At the end of his first season, Lienhart was signed permanently for €800,000,<ref name=diarioas>{{cite news|last1=De la Rosa|first1=Álvario|title=Lienhart: un central de 800.000€|trans-title=Lienhart: an €800,000 defender|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2015/10/16/primera/1445018976_872727.html|accessdate=17 October 2015|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|date=17 October 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> and was subsequently promoted to [[Real Madrid Castilla|the reserves]] by manager [[Zinedine Zidane]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/07/05/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1436084389.html|title=El nuevo ejército de Zizou|trans-title=''Zizou's'' new army|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> He made his debut for the B-team on 30 August 2015, playing the full 90 minutes of a 2–1 win at [[CF Rayo Majadahonda]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/noticias/2015/08/1-2-el-castilla-remonta-con-un-doblete-de-mariano|title=1–2: El Castilla remonta con un doblete de Mariano|trans-title=1–2: Castilla comebacks with a Mariano's double|publisher=Real Madrid's official website|date=30 August 2015|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>

On 3 October 2015, Lienhart scored his first Castilla goal, equalising for a 1–1 draw at [[Sestao River Club]] by heading in [[Martin Ødegaard]]'s [[corner kick]].<ref>{{cite news|title=1-1: Castilla get a point in Sestao|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/10/1-1-castilla-get-a-point-in-sestao|accessdate=17 October 2015|publisher=Real Madrid's official website|date=3 October 2015}}</ref> Two weeks later, amid an injury crisis, he was included in the main squad for the first time by manager [[Rafael Benítez]], for a [[La Liga]] match against [[Levante UD]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Ramos and Arbeloa late losses for Levante game|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/10/16/en/football/real_madrid/1445018857.html|accessdate=17 October 2015|publisher=Marca|date=16 October 2015}}</ref> he was unused in the 3–0 win at the [[Santiago Bernabéu Stadium]]. He made his first team debut on 2 December 2015, replacing [[James Rodríguez]] in a 3–1 [[Copa del Rey]] away win against [[Cádiz CF]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2015_16/copa/dieciseisavos/ida/cad_rma/|title=Victoria indebida|trans-title=Unduly win|publisher=Marca|language=es|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>

===SC Freiburg===
On 5 July 2017, Lienhart was loaned to [[SC Freiburg]] for one year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scfreiburg.com/news/philipp-lienhart-kommt-aus-madrid|title=Philipp Lienhart kommt aus Madrid|publisher=scfreiburg.com|language=de|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=5 July 2017|archive-date=13 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013065025/https://www.scfreiburg.com/news/philipp-lienhart-kommt-aus-madrid|url-status=dead}}</ref> In June 2018, the club announced they had signed him permanently from Real Madrid. The transfer fee was estimated at €2 million plus bonuses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lienhart-Transfer: Hartenbachs Dank an Real |url=https://www.kicker.de/lienhart-transfer_hartenbachs-dank-an-real-725152/artikel |access-date=5 June 2018 |work=kicker Online |date=5 June 2018 |language=German}}</ref>

==International career==
Lienhart represented [[Austria national football team|Austria]] at the [[Austria national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[Austria national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[Austria national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Austria national under-21 football team|under-21 levels]].

Lienhart got his first call up to the senior [[Austria national football team|Austria]] side after [[Sebastian Prödl]] withdrew through injury for [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualifiers against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lienhart und Sax ersetzen Prödl und Sabitzer |url=http://www.nachrichten.at/sport/fussball/fussball-oesterreich/Lienhart-und-Sax-ersetzen-Proedl-und-Sabitzer;art127116,2667952 |accessdate=4 September 2017 |publisher=nachrichten.at|date=4 September 2017}}</ref> He made his debut playing the full 90 minutes of the final match of the qualifying campaign, a 1–0 win against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] in October.<ref>{{cite news|title=Philipp Lienhart: Debüt im Kinder-Riegel|url=https://www.kicker.de/philipp-lienhart_debuet-im-kinder-riegel-708047/artikel|access-date=10 October 2017|work=kicker Online|date=10 October 2017|language=German}}</ref>

His first goal for [[Austria national football team|Austria]] came during a [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying match]] against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 16 November 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/match/2036484--estonia-vs-austria/|title=Estonia vs Austria|work=[[UEFA]]}}</ref>

